[1] Norovirus, Yellowstone National Park - USA
Date: Fri 9 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Billings Gazette, Fri 9 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.billingsgazette.com/index.php?tl=1&display=rednews/2004/07/09/bu
ild/wyoming/25-yllstn-outbreak.inc>

USA: outbreak of norovirus infection at Yellowstone National Park
-----------------------------------------------
More than 130 visitors and workers became ill in Yellowstone National Park
in late June 2004 during an outbreak of a highly infectious virus at Old
Faithful and Lake. The cause of the illnesses appears to be a norovirus, a
group of viruses that can cause stomach flu, also known as gastroenteritis.
It is the same virus that has affected hundreds on cruise ships, and,
caused earlier outbreaks at Yellowstone and Grand Canyon National Parks.
The virus can cause vomiting, diarrhea, nausea, and stomach cramping.
Symptoms can come on quickly, and, usually, last one to 2 days. "We're very
nervous system-wide about this virus. Not because it's life-threatening or
severe, but because it's so prevalent," said Charles Higgins, director of
the National Park Service's Office of Public Health. Most of the afflicted
people in Yellowstone started getting sick during the last week of June
2004. Employees at a clinic in the Park noticed the upswing in
gastrointestinal problems and contacted authorities at Park Service
headquarters. Investigators said it appears that the virus spread
person-to-person, and, through contact with objects such as doorknobs. "It
doesn't look like it got into the food service systems, which is really
almost a miracle," Higgins said. "That probably means (the concession
company) did something well."
The outbreak wasn't surprising, especially at a place like Old Faithful,
where people often congregate in close proximity, Higgins said. It affected
concession employees the most, because they live in dormitories and share
facilities, he said. It's still unclear where the virus came from and
exactly how it spread, but Higgins said it doesn't take much for this virus
to rapidly spread. "You might have a visitor who came in ill with the virus
and threw up in their room. Then, the housekeeper cleans it up, that person
becomes ill, and they go back to the dorm, throw up there, and then boom,
50 other people are ill," Higgins said. Park officials said 53 visitors
became ill, together with 71 concession employees and 8 Park Service
workers. Most people were sick for only a day or so, and the outbreak
tapered off sharply by the 4th of July weekend.
Park officials, including a federal Public Health Service worker at
Yellowstone full time, responded quickly to the outbreak, and, got
cooperation from the Wyoming Department of Health and the concession
company, said Cheryl Matthews, a Yellowstone spokeswoman. Xanterra Parks
and Resorts, the concessions company, took extra steps, including wiping
down door handles and cleaning bathrooms more frequently, she said.
Norovirus makes an estimated 23 million people ill every year, according to
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The virus is most commonly
spread through eating contaminated food, touching contaminated surfaces,
and having direct contact with people with symptoms. "The virus, formerly
known as Norwalk virus, is very infectious and tends to take advantage of
people living [in close proximity]," Higgins said.
In recent years, there have been outbreaks at Yellowstone's Fishing Bridge
and at Grand Canyon. Higgins said this year's [2004] outbreak at
Yellowstone is in the "midrange in terms of size and length of time." 4
investigators interviewed people who became sick, took samples, and looked
over medical records. The information will be sent to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention for analysis. In the next week or 2, a
report will be issued about the outbreak, including an examination of how
it spread and what steps could be taken for preventing a similar outbreak
in the future.
[Byline: Mike Stark]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The challenges of preventing and controlling such outbreaks in the park
cannot be overstated. This moderator was involved in investigating an
outbreak of probable norovirus gastroenteritis in Yellowstone National Park
in the late '70s, and at that time, there was a "floating" denominator at
risk within the park during the peak tourist period of approximately 35 000
individuals daily. This included park employees, concession employees and
visitors. Visitors included daytime only visitors who came for the day and
left to stay elsewhere, those who were staying at lodges within the park,
those who were camping at park campground areas and those staying in
personal recreational vehicles. The overnighting visitors were there for
varying lengths of stay with the majority estimated to be approximately 4
days (reflected by the revolving menu at the park restaurants -- a 4 day
cycle). Hence, the population at risk of infection is rather large, as is
the potential for reintroduction of infection with high volume of new
arrivals on a daily basis. As mentioned in the starting sentence -- the
challenges of preventing and controlling such outbreaks in the park cannot
be overstated. - Mod.MPP]
