[2] Norovirus, community epidemic - Australia (NSW)
Date: Tue 13 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Herald Sun online, Tue 13 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,10128176%255E1702
,00.html>

Australia: gastroenteritis outbreak in New South Wales strikes 6000
-----------------------------------------------
More than 6000 people in New South Wales (NSW) have been hit by a virus
infection in 2004, in what health authorities are calling a gastroenteritis
epidemic. NSW Health today [Tue 13 Jul 2004] warned that 2004's outbreak of
the highly infectious disease, caused by norovirus infection, had already
overtaken 2003's total of 3570 cases. Noroviruses cause severe vomiting and
diarrhea.
The health authority's communicable disease director, Dr. Jeremy McAnulty,
said the increased incidence of the virus was placing added pressure on
hospital emergency departments. He said elderly people in aged care homes
accounted for more than 71 per cent of cases reported. Nursing homes,
hospitals, child-care centers and schools were worst affected, with the
upsurge possibly due to better reporting practices within those institutions.
"The symptoms tend to be a sudden onset of pretty violent vomiting, and
nausea, and then diarrhea ... and sometimes you get muscle aches and
fever," Dr. McAnulty said. "Most people bounce back pretty quickly, but
it's really important that you drink lots of fluids so you rehydrate."
Dr. McAnulty said the gastroenteritis virus known as norovirus is
particularly prevalent in winter, and is spread following direct contact
with an infected person. Symptoms sometimes took up to 3 days to appear. In
the worst case, dehydration from vomiting and diarrhea could be fatal for
anyone who was frail, he said. But most people recovered within a few days.
"There's no specific treatment except for re-hydration," Dr. McAnulty said.
Exposure to the virus could be reduced by thoroughly washing hands before
handling and eating food and before [and after] using a toilet. Anyone
contracting the virus was urged to avoid preparing food for others until at
least 2 days after recovering, and, to stay at home.
