[3] Norovirus outbreak, hospital based - UK (Scotland)
Date: 16 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source:
<http://icrenfrewshire.icnetwork.co.uk/news/localnews/pdenews/pdenews/tm_objectid=14432867&method=full&siteid=63858&headline=sickness-bug-closes-two--wards-at-rah-name_page.html>

UK: Sickness bug closes 2 wards at Royal Alexandra Hospital
--------------------
2 wards at the Royal Alexandra Hospital have been closed after a new
outbreak of a nasty stomach bug which is attacking patients and staff.
An infection which causes vomiting and diarrhoea is spreading throughout
the Paisley hospital and has so far hit 43 people.
Now children have been banned from visiting any of the wards affected.
A total of 37 patients - many of whom are elderly - have been affected and
6 members of staff have all fallen ill as a result of the virus.
The bug means that NHS bosses have had to shut wards 4 and 7 - both of
which are care of the elderly wards - to new admissions.
Patients in another elderly ward at the hospital - ward 3 - have also
fallen ill, while patients in wards 11 and 14 - medical wards - have also
been affected.
It's the 2nd time in just a few months that RAH bosses have had to deal
with such an outbreak.
A similar bug swept through the hospital in March and April, with more than
100 people being affected that time.
And 4 of the wards that were affected then have also been hit by the bug
again. Patients in wards 3, 4, 7 and 14 were all struck down by the virus -
which usually affects people for 2 to 3 days.
Hospital chiefs have set up a special control-of-infection team to deal
with the outbreak, which began more than a week ago.
Mary Morgan, the service general manager, explained that a series of
measures had been brought in to try to stop the infection from spreading
further.
Youngsters under the age of 12 have been barred from visiting family and
friends in the 5 affected wards and people who have been ill in the last
week are also being urged not to visit.
Ms Morgan said: "Infection-control precautions are in place and we suggest
that anyone who has experienced symptoms of diarrhoea or vomiting within
the last 7 days should not visit the hospital. Within the affected ward
areas we can only permit 2 visitors per bed and no children under the age
of 12 should visit."
She added: "The hospital's control of infection team is monitoring the
outbreak daily. The wards will be re-opened once we are sure that the
infection is clear - at least 48 hours after the last patient showed any
symptoms.
"We are providing visitors to each of the wards affected with relevant
information on the outbreak of infection."
