[4] Viral gastroenteritis, shellfish - New Zealand (Bay of Islands)
Date: 16 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: TV NZ
<http://tvnz.co.nz/view/news_health_story_skin/436182%3fformat=html>

New Zealand: Sewage virus in food supply
----------------------
An ESR scientist confirmed that viruses found in sewage have been
identified in shellfish at 2 sites in the Bay of Islands.
People are reporting bouts of food poisoning from pipi and cockles in Te
Haumi and Waitangi and the shellfish are being tested as part of a 3 year
study.
Gail Greening said samples taken at the sites earlier this year show the
presence of viruses that cause gastroenteritis.
Greening said the study is testing shellfish from around New Zealand for
viruses and other organisms that could be used as an indicator that viruses
are present.
Health protection officer, Tahi Morton, says people should not eat pipis,
cockles or other kaimoana from Opua to Te Haumi, for at least a month.
He says pollution in the area is ongoing, and signs which warn against
eating shellfish should stay up indefinitely until the water quality improves.
But for one Bay of Islands woman the warning is not new.
She has been campaigning for years against sewage pollution saying her
people are regularly poisoned by it.
She says testing since January has repeatedly found sewage viruses in
shellfish that many Maori depend on to feed their families.
The viruses found in shellfish around Paihia and Waitangi can cause
symptoms including severe vomiting and diarrhoea. [While the organism isn't
specified it is likely to be a member of the norovirus family. - Mod.MPP]
